+% ============================================================
+\subsection{Research Track: Quasinormal Swirl Spectroscopy and Spectral-Robustness Gate}
+    \label{sec:rt_quasinormal_swirl_spectroscopy}
+
+    \subsubsection*{Status, scope, and terminology}
+
+        \noindent
+        \textbf{Status:} [RESEARCH-TRACK / NOT CANONICAL].
+        This subsection transfers the mathematically useful parts of quasinormal-mode
+        spectroscopy to perturbations of resolved SST vortex states
+        \cite{BertiEtAl2026BlackHoleSpectroscopy}.  It does \emph{not} identify an SST
+        knot with a Kerr black hole, does not assume an event horizon, and does not
+        import the Einstein equations.  The transferable content is the analysis of
+        open, non-normal, or coarse-grained evolution through response poles,
+        adjoint modes, resolvents, pseudospectra, nonlinear combination frequencies,
+        and controlled mode-identification tests.
+
+        To avoid an ontological overstatement, this track uses the term
+        \emph{quasinormal swirl mode} (QSM).  A QSM is an SST response resonance with a
+        complex frequency.  The term \emph{QNM} remains reserved for the orthodox
+        black-hole or analogue-gravity comparison.
+
+        Three objects must remain distinct:
+        \begin{enumerate}
+            \item the real normal-mode tower of a closed conservative carrier, as in
+            Section~\ref{subsec:spectral_locked_carriers};
+            \item the phenomenological Lorentzian response model of
+            Section~\ref{sec:resonance-selection-principle};
+            \item QSMs defined as poles or isolated spectral resonances of a specified
+            linearized SST evolution problem.
+        \end{enumerate}
+        A fitted damped sinusoid or an FFT peak alone is not a QSM certification.
+
+    \subsubsection*{Relative-equilibrium background and linearized Euler operator}
+
+        Let \(\mathbf v_0(\mathbf x)\) and \(p_0(\mathbf x)\) be a resolved,
+        divergence-free SST background in a frame in which the chosen vortex ring or
+        knot is stationary:
+        \begin{align}
+            \nabla\cdot\mathbf v_0 &= 0,
+            \\
+            (\mathbf v_0\cdot\nabla)\mathbf v_0
+            &=
+            -\frac{1}{\rhoF}\nabla p_0.
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_background_euler}
+        \end{align}
+        A translating or rotating vortex is therefore treated as a
+        \emph{relative equilibrium}; the translation and rotation generators belong to
+        the frame definition rather than to the internal mode spectrum.  Failure to
+        remove those rigid motions produces spurious low-frequency modes.
+
+        Write
+        \begin{equation}
+            \mathbf v
+            =
+            \mathbf v_0+\epsilon\mathbf u+O(\epsilon^2),
+            \qquad
+            p
+            =
+            p_0+\epsilon\pi+O(\epsilon^2),
+        \end{equation}
+        with \(\nabla\cdot\mathbf u=0\).  The first-order incompressible Euler system is
+        \begin{equation}
+            \partial_t\mathbf u
+            +
+            (\mathbf v_0\cdot\nabla)\mathbf u
+            +
+            (\mathbf u\cdot\nabla)\mathbf v_0
+            =
+            -\frac{1}{\rhoF}\nabla\pi.
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_linearized_euler}
+        \end{equation}
+        Introducing the Leray projector \(\mathbb P\) onto the admissible
+        divergence-free subspace gives
+        \begin{equation}
+            \partial_t\mathbf u
+            =
+            \mathcal L_K\mathbf u,
+            \qquad
+            \mathcal L_K\mathbf u
+            =
+            -\mathbb P
+            \left[
+                (\mathbf v_0\cdot\nabla)\mathbf u
+                +
+                (\mathbf u\cdot\nabla)\mathbf v_0
+            \right]
+            +
+            \mathcal L_{\rm frame}\mathbf u.
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_linear_operator}
+        \end{equation}
+        Here \(\mathcal L_{\rm frame}\) contains only the explicitly declared
+        co-translating or co-rotating frame generators and vanishes for a stationary
+        laboratory-frame background.  Equations
+        \eqref{eq:rt_qss_background_euler}--\eqref{eq:rt_qss_linear_operator} are the
+        orthodox incompressible-flow linearization used as the starting point for this
+        SST track \cite{MajdaBertozzi2002}.
+
+        The domain, core profile, regularization, topological sector, outer boundary,
+        and allowed flux conditions are part of the operator definition.  A spectrum
+        quoted without this metadata is non-reproducible.
+
+    \subsubsection*{Complex frequencies and admissible damping mechanisms}
+
+        A modal ansatz
+        \begin{equation}
+            \mathbf u_j(\mathbf x,t)
+            =
+            \mathbf q_j(\mathbf x)e^{s_jt}
+            =
+            \mathbf q_j(\mathbf x)e^{-i\omega_jt},
+            \qquad
+            s_j=-i\omega_j,
+        \end{equation}
+        yields
+        \begin{equation}
+            \mathcal L_K\mathbf q_j
+            =
+            s_j\mathbf q_j.
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_eigenproblem}
+        \end{equation}
+        With
+        \begin{equation}
+            \omega_j
+            =
+            \omega_{R,j}-i\gamma_j,
+            \qquad
+            \gamma_j>0,
+        \end{equation}
+        the amplitude behaves as
+        \(e^{-\gamma_jt}\cos(\omega_{R,j}t+\phi_j)\).
+
+        \textbf{[INVISCID CONSISTENCY GATE].}
+        In an exactly closed, fully resolved, inviscid system, damping may not be
+        inserted as an unexplained friction coefficient.  A negative imaginary part
+        must be traced to at least one declared mechanism:
+        \begin{enumerate}
+            \item advective energy or vorticity flux through an open boundary;
+            \item phase mixing or transfer into a continuous spectrum;
+            \item transfer into unresolved internal degrees of freedom under an
+            explicitly declared coarse graining;
+            \item projection onto a local observable while the total conservative
+            state continues to evolve.
+        \end{enumerate}
+        A numerical sponge or absorbing layer is a computational boundary treatment,
+        not a physical SST damping mechanism, unless the extracted pole converges as
+        the layer is moved outward and weakened.
+
+        The linewidth convention is fixed throughout this track by
+        \begin{equation}
+            \boxed{
+                \gamma_j
+                =
+                \frac{1}{\tau_{A,j}}
+                =
+                \frac{\omega_{R,j}}{2Q_j},
+                \qquad
+                \Delta\omega_{{\rm FWHM},j}=2\gamma_j
+            }.
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_linewidth_convention}
+        \end{equation}
+        Thus \(\tau_{A,j}\) is the amplitude-decay time.  An energy-decay time would be
+        \(\tau_{E,j}=1/(2\gamma_j)\), and these two conventions must not be mixed.
+
+    \subsubsection*{Pole definition, residues, and continuous spectrum}
+
+        Define the retarded resolvent
+        \begin{equation}
+            \mathcal R_K(s)
+            =
+            (sI-\mathcal L_K)^{-1}.
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_resolvent}
+        \end{equation}
+        A certified QSM is an isolated pole \(s_j\) of the analytically continued
+        response, or an isolated eigenvalue of a rigorously specified time-evolution
+        generator on the chosen function space.  Near a simple pole,
+        \begin{equation}
+            \chi_K(\omega)
+            =
+            \frac{\mathcal B_j}
+            {\omega-\omega_j}
+            +
+            \chi_{\rm reg}(\omega),
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_local_pole}
+        \end{equation}
+        where \(\mathcal B_j\) is a residue fixed by the forcing and observable.
+        Consequently, the Lorentzian forms in
+        Eqs.~\eqref{eq:RK_lorentzian} and
+        \eqref{eq:frequency_response_chi} are local isolated-pole approximations, not
+        primary definitions of the spectrum.
+
+        In general the response may contain both discrete resonances and a continuous
+        contribution:
+        \begin{equation}
+            A(t)
+            =
+            \sum_j
+            C_j e^{-i\omega_jt}
+            +
+            \int_{\mathcal C}
+            C(\omega)e^{-i\omega t}\,d\omega.
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_poles_and_continuum}
+        \end{equation}
+        The second term may produce phase-mixed transients or algebraic tails.
+        Therefore a stable multi-exponential fit over one short time interval does not
+        establish completeness of the pole sum
+        \cite{BertiEtAl2026BlackHoleSpectroscopy}.
+
+    \subsubsection*{Adjoint modes, biorthogonality, and first-order sensitivity}
+
+        For a non-normal evolution generator, right and adjoint modes satisfy
+        \begin{align}
+            \mathcal L_K\mathbf q_j
+            &=
+            s_j\mathbf q_j,
+            \\
+            \mathcal L_K^\dagger\mathbf q_j^\dagger
+            &=
+            s_j^\ast\mathbf q_j^\dagger.
+        \end{align}
+        With an explicitly declared energy or Sobolev inner product, the modes may be
+        normalized biorthogonally:
+        \begin{equation}
+            \left\langle
+                \mathbf q_i^\dagger,
+                \mathbf q_j
+            \right\rangle_E
+            =
+            \delta_{ij}.
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_biorthogonality}
+        \end{equation}
+        For a small structured perturbation
+        \(\delta\mathcal L_K\), the simple-eigenvalue shift is
+        \begin{equation}
+            \delta s_j
+            =
+            \frac{
+                \left\langle
+                    \mathbf q_j^\dagger,
+                    \delta\mathcal L_K\mathbf q_j
+                \right\rangle_E
+            }{
+                \left\langle
+                    \mathbf q_j^\dagger,
+                    \mathbf q_j
+                \right\rangle_E
+            }
+            +
+            O(\|\delta\mathcal L_K\|^2).
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_adjoint_shift}
+        \end{equation}
+        A useful conditioning diagnostic is
+        \begin{equation}
+            \kappa_j
+            =
+            \frac{
+                \|\mathbf q_j^\dagger\|_E
+                \|\mathbf q_j\|_E
+            }{
+                \left|
+                    \left\langle
+                        \mathbf q_j^\dagger,
+                        \mathbf q_j
+                    \right\rangle_E
+                \right|
+            }.
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_condition_number}
+        \end{equation}
+        Large \(\kappa_j\) means that the pole can move strongly under a small change in
+        core profile, embedding, boundary, or discretization.  Reporting only
+        \(\omega_j\) without \(\kappa_j\) can therefore misclassify a fragile numerical
+        overtone as a robust physical mode.
+
+    \subsubsection*{Pseudospectral robustness gate}
+
+        The \(\varepsilon\)-pseudospectrum is
+        \begin{equation}
+            \boxed{
+                \sigma_\varepsilon(\mathcal L_K)
+                =
+                \left\{
+                    s\in\mathbb C:
+                    \left\|
+                        (sI-\mathcal L_K)^{-1}
+                    \right\|_E
+                    >
+                    \varepsilon^{-1}
+                \right\}
+            }.
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_pseudospectrum}
+        \end{equation}
+        It measures where small operator perturbations can create large responses or
+        large spectral shifts.  This is required because open gravitational spectra
+        provide explicit examples in which very small potential perturbations strongly
+        displace overtones \cite{JaramilloPanossoMacedoAlSheikh2021,
+        BertiEtAl2026BlackHoleSpectroscopy}.
+
+        For SST, the perturbation classes must be separated:
+        \begin{align}
+            \delta\mathcal L_{\rm geom}
+            &: \text{embedding, reach, core-profile, and contact-map changes},
+            \\
+            \delta\mathcal L_{\rm num}
+            &: \text{mesh, quadrature, regularization, and timestep changes},
+            \\
+            \delta\mathcal L_{\rm env}
+            &: \text{outer-flow, wall, background-vorticity, and probe changes}.
+        \end{align}
+        A QSM is \emph{spectrally robust} only if the relevant
+        pseudospectral contours remain localized on the perturbation scale actually
+        admitted by the benchmark.  Broad contours are not automatically a
+        falsification; they require the mode to be labelled \emph{fragile} and prevent
+        its promotion as a precision observable.
+
+    \subsubsection*{Conditional trapped-characteristic/eikonal route}
+
+        A light-ring formula may not be copied into SST.  The required starting point is
+        the principal symbol of the actual SST perturbation equations,
+        \begin{equation}
+            D_K(\mathbf x,\mathbf k,\omega)=0.
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_principal_symbol}
+        \end{equation}
+        Its characteristic rays satisfy
+        \begin{equation}
+            \dot{\mathbf x}
+            =
+            \frac{\partial D_K}{\partial\mathbf k},
+            \qquad
+            \dot{\mathbf k}
+            =
+            -\frac{\partial D_K}{\partial\mathbf x}.
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_characteristic_rays}
+        \end{equation}
+        Only if a specific perturbation branch possesses an unstable periodic
+        characteristic with orbital frequency \(\Omega_\star\) and transverse
+        Lyapunov exponent \(\Lambda_\star\) may SST test the asymptotic hypothesis
+        \begin{equation}
+            \boxed{
+                \omega_{mn}^{\rm QSM}
+                \simeq
+                m\Omega_\star
+                -
+                i\left(n+\frac12\right)\Lambda_\star
+            }
+            \qquad
+            (m\gg1).
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_eikonal_hypothesis}
+        \end{equation}
+        This structure is motivated by the orthodox eikonal QNM relation
+        \cite{CardosoMirandaBertiWitekZanchin2009,
+        BertiEtAl2026BlackHoleSpectroscopy}, but Eq.~\eqref{eq:rt_qss_eikonal_hypothesis}
+        is only an SST research hypothesis.
+
+        \textbf{[CRITICAL GATE].}
+        Incompressible Euler flow does not generically supply an acoustic null cone or
+        a scalar wave branch.  The characteristic branch, localization, WKB ordering,
+        and large-\(m\) limit must therefore be derived before
+        \(\Omega_\star\) or \(\Lambda_\star\) is assigned.  Failure of this derivation
+        blocks the entire trapped-characteristic route but does not block the
+        resolvent-based QSM programme.
+
+    \subsubsection*{Second-order combination modes}
+
+        Expand a perturbation variable as
+        \begin{equation}
+            q
+            =
+            \epsilon q^{(1)}
+            +
+            \epsilon^2q^{(2)}
+            +
+            O(\epsilon^3).
+        \end{equation}
+        The second-order equation has the schematic form
+        \begin{equation}
+            \left(
+                \partial_t-\mathcal L_K
+            \right)q^{(2)}
+            =
+            \mathcal N_2
+            \left[
+                q^{(1)},q^{(1)}
+            \right].
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_second_order_equation}
+        \end{equation}
+        If the first-order field contains modes \(a\) and \(b\), the quadratic source
+        contains candidate frequencies
+        \begin{equation}
+            \omega_{ab}^{(+)}
+            =
+            \omega_a+\omega_b,
+            \qquad
+            \omega_{ab}^{(-)}
+            =
+            \omega_a-\omega_b^\ast.
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_combination_frequencies}
+        \end{equation}
+        Their decay rates add.  For an azimuthally resolved background the corresponding
+        selection rules include \(m_{ab}=m_a+m_b\) for the sum channel and
+        \(m_{ab}=m_a-m_b\) for the difference channel, subject to the actual parity and
+        topology constraints of the chosen state.
+
+        In the perturbative regime,
+        \begin{equation}
+            A_{ab}^{(2)}
+            \propto
+            A_a^{(1)}A_b^{(1)}
+            \propto
+            \epsilon^2.
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_quadratic_amplitude_scaling}
+        \end{equation}
+        A peak near a sum or difference frequency is not sufficient: its amplitude must
+        exhibit the quadratic scaling and its symmetry label must satisfy the selection
+        rule.  This provides a direct nonlinear benchmark inspired by quadratic
+        black-hole modes, without importing their dynamics
+        \cite{BertiEtAl2026BlackHoleSpectroscopy}.
+
+    \subsubsection*{Mode avoidance and exceptional-point scan}
+
+        For two interacting modes, a local reduced model is
+        \begin{equation}
+            H_{\rm eff}
+            =
+            \begin{pmatrix}
+                s_1 & g_{12}\\
+                g_{21} & s_2
+            \end{pmatrix},
+        \end{equation}
+        with eigenvalues
+        \begin{equation}
+            s_\pm
+            =
+            \frac{s_1+s_2}{2}
+            \pm
+            \sqrt{
+                \left(
+                    \frac{s_1-s_2}{2}
+                \right)^2
+                +
+                g_{12}g_{21}
+            }.
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_two_mode_eigenvalues}
+        \end{equation}
+        An exceptional point requires the square-root discriminant to vanish and the
+        eigenvectors to coalesce.  Because this is one complex condition, two
+        independent real control parameters are generically required.  Candidate SST
+        scans include
+        \begin{equation}
+            \left(
+                \frac{a_{\rm core}}{L_K},
+                \frac{\Gamma_K}{v_{\rm ref}L_K}
+            \right),
+            \qquad
+            \left(
+                \mathrm{Tw},
+                \frac{\operatorname{reach}(K)}{L_K}
+            \right).
+        \end{equation}
+        A credible identification requires eigenvector exchange, adjoint-norm growth,
+        and the expected square-root parameter dependence; an avoided crossing in a
+        frequency plot alone is insufficient
+        \cite{BertiEtAl2026BlackHoleSpectroscopy}.
+
+    \subsubsection*{Dimensionless scaling and canonical numerical values}
+
+        For any mode family define
+        \begin{equation}
+            \widehat\omega_j
+            =
+            \omega_j
+            \frac{L_{\rm ref}}{v_{\rm ref}}.
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_dimensionless_frequency}
+        \end{equation}
+        The pair \((L_{\rm ref},v_{\rm ref})\) must match the localization scale of the
+        mode.  The core reference choice
+        \(L_{\rm ref}=\rc\) and \(v_{\rm ref}=\vnorm\) gives
+        \begin{align}
+            t_c
+            &=
+            \frac{\rc}{\vnorm}
+            =
+            1.28808868\times10^{-21}\ \mathrm{s},
+            \\
+            \Omega_c
+            &=
+            \frac{\vnorm}{\rc}
+            =
+            7.76344066\times10^{20}\ \mathrm{s^{-1}},
+            \\
+            f_c
+            &=
+            \frac{\Omega_c}{2\pi}
+            =
+            1.23558996\times10^{20}\ \mathrm{Hz}.
+            \label{eq:rt_qss_canonical_scales}
+        \end{align}
+        These values are reference scales, not predictions that every global knot mode
+        lies at \(\Omega_c\).  A trefoil-scale mode must instead use a resolved global
+        length such as \(L_K\), \(R_{\rm horn}\), or a certified localization length.
+
+    \subsubsection*{Numerical certification ladder}
+
+        The minimum numerical programme is:
+        \begin{enumerate}
+            \item \textbf{Background certification.}
+            Construct a vortex ring first and then a trefoil relative equilibrium.
+            Record Euler residual, divergence residual, impulse, circulation, helicity,
+            topology, reach, and core profile.
+
+            \item \textbf{Consistent tangent operator.}
+            Linearize the same discretized evolution used for the nonlinear run or
+            validate the continuum linearization against finite differences.  Enforce
+            the divergence-free projection and remove rigid translation/rotation modes.
+
+            \item \textbf{Dual extraction.}
+            Compute leading eigenvalues with an Arnoldi or Jacobi--Davidson method and
+            independently extract damped components from small-amplitude time-domain
+            data using matrix-pencil, Prony, or validated dynamic-mode decomposition.
+
+            \item \textbf{Resolution and boundary sequence.}
+            Vary spatial resolution, timestep, domain size, core regularization, and
+            absorbing-boundary placement independently.  Extrapolate before assigning
+            a physical frequency.
+
+            \item \textbf{Adjoint and pseudospectral audit.}
+            Compute left modes, \(\kappa_j\), resolvent norms, and structured
+            perturbations from
+            \(\delta\mathcal L_{\rm geom}\),
+            \(\delta\mathcal L_{\rm num}\), and
+            \(\delta\mathcal L_{\rm env}\).
+
+            \item \textbf{Nonlinear amplitude sweep.}
+            Repeat at several perturbation amplitudes.  Linear poles must be
+            amplitude-independent over a declared interval, while quadratic
+            combination amplitudes follow
+            Eq.~\eqref{eq:rt_qss_quadratic_amplitude_scaling}.
+
+            \item \textbf{Model hierarchy.}
+            Validate the axisymmetric ring benchmark before interpreting a knotted
+            spectrum.  The default first knot is the resolved trefoil \(3_1\); extended
+            knot families enter only after the ring and trefoil pass the same gates.
+        \end{enumerate}
+
+        Passive tracer particles should be disabled during the eigensolve and restored
+        afterward.  They are visualization degrees of freedom, not part of
+        \(\mathcal L_K\), unless a benchmark explicitly promotes them to an active
+        coupled field.
+
+    \subsubsection*{Preregistered pass/fail criteria}
+
+        A mode may be labelled a \emph{certified numerical QSM candidate} only if:
+        \begin{enumerate}
+            \item the complex frequency converges to within a preregistered tolerance,
+            initially \(1\%\) for the fundamental ring and trefoil modes;
+            \item time-domain and operator-based estimates agree within their combined
+            uncertainty;
+            \item divergence and background-residual errors decrease under refinement;
+            \item the knot type and resolved tube do not undergo reconnection during
+            the linear measurement window;
+            \item boundary dependence is either negligible at the tolerance level or
+            explicitly identified as the physical open-system mechanism;
+            \item the linewidth, \(Q\), and decay-time convention satisfies
+            Eq.~\eqref{eq:rt_qss_linewidth_convention};
+            \item the residual after subtracting the pole model is tested for a
+            continuous-spectrum or tail contribution.
+        \end{enumerate}
+
+        Promotion beyond a numerical candidate additionally requires robustness under
+        physically admissible geometry perturbations and a reproducible observable
+        coupling coefficient or residue.
+
+    \subsubsection*{Analogue-experiment discipline}
+
+        Hydrodynamic analogue experiments demonstrate that complex vortex-response
+        spectra can be measured and that many counter-rotating resonances may be
+        excited in one nonequilibrium experiment
+        \cite{TorresPatrickRichartzWeinfurtner2020,
+        BertiEtAl2026BlackHoleSpectroscopy}.  This supports the feasibility of a
+        spectroscopy workflow, but it is not evidence for SST ontology.  Any proposed
+        analogue must independently vary and report dispersion, background vorticity,
+        asymmetry, finite-size effects, and boundary reflections.
+
+    \subsubsection*{Falsifiers and promotion rule}
+
+        This track is falsified or blocked for a stated configuration if:
+        \begin{enumerate}
